docs/guides/01-getting-started.md
     1‚Üí# Getting Started
     3‚Üí## Installing Superstruct
     5‚ÜíTo install Superstruct run:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí```bash
     8‚Üínpm install --save superstruct
     9‚Üí```
    10‚Üí
    11‚ÜíAnd then you can import it:
    12‚Üí
    13‚Üí```ts
    14‚Üíimport { object, string, number } from 'superstruct'
    15‚Üí
    16‚Üíconst User = object({
    17‚Üí  id: number(),
    18‚Üí  name: string(),
    19‚Üí})
    20‚Üí```
    21‚Üí
    22‚ÜíIf you'd like, you can use a wildcard import:
    23‚Üí
    24‚Üí```ts
    25‚Üíimport * as s from 'superstruct'
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üíconst User = s.object({
    28‚Üí  id: s.number(),
    29‚Üí  name: s.string(),
    30‚Üí})
    31‚Üí```
    32‚Üí
    33‚ÜíIf you'd rather use a `<script>` tag, you can use the UMD build:
    34‚Üí
    35‚Üí```html
    36‚Üí<script src="https://unpkg.com/superstruct/lib/index.cjs"></script>
    37‚Üí```
    38‚Üí
    39‚ÜíThis will expose the `Superstruct` global.
    40‚Üí
    41‚Üí## Defining Structs ‚Ä¶
docs/guides/02-validating-data.md
     1‚Üí# Validating Data
     3‚ÜíSuperstruct is designed to let you validate any data, ensuring that it matches a specific schema. In this guide we'll show you some of the possibilities.
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí## Primitive Values ‚Ä¶
    37‚Üí## Composed Values ‚Ä¶
   114‚Üí## Optional Values ‚Ä¶
   157‚Üí## Custom Values ‚Ä¶
docs/guides/03-coercing-data.md
     1‚Üí# Coercing Data
     3‚ÜíSometimes while validating input data you'll actually want to "coerce" it to change it in someway to help validation pass. The most common example of this is adding default values to properties, but it can also be used to parse multiple input formats, or cleanup inconsistent data.
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíTo allow for these use cases, Superstruct has a concept called "coercion", which allows you to encode specific logic about how to transform a piece of data before validating it.
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí## Default Values ‚Ä¶
    49‚Üí## Custom Coercions ‚Ä¶
docs/guides/04-refining-validation.md
     1‚Üí# Refining Validation
     3‚ÜíThere are some cases where you want to create a validation that is more fine-grained than a "type". For example, you might want not just a `string`, but a specific format of string. Or not just a `User`, but a user that is also an administrator.
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíFor these situations, you can use "refinements". Refinements allow you to create a new struct that is derived from an existing struct with an extra bit of validation layered on top.
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí## Built-in Refinements ‚Ä¶
    47‚Üí## Custom Refinements ‚Ä¶
docs/guides/05-handling-errors.md
     1‚Üí# Handling Errors
     3‚ÜíBy default Superstruct throws errors that are easy to understand for developers. This means that out of the box you'll get nice errors messages that help you track down why a piece of data is invalid.
     4‚Üí
     5‚ÜíFor example, consider a simple `User` struct:
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí```ts
     8‚Üíconst User = object({
     9‚Üí  id: number(),
    10‚Üí  name: string(),
    11‚Üí  email: email(),
    12‚Üí})
    13‚Üí```
    14‚Üí
    15‚ÜíIf you pass in an invalid email, an error will be thrown:
    16‚Üí
    17‚Üí```ts
    18‚Üíconst data = {
    19‚Üí  id: 1,
    20‚Üí  name: 'Alex',
    21‚Üí  email: false,
    22‚Üí}
    23‚Üí
    24‚Üíassert(data, User)
    25‚Üí// StructError: At path: email -- Expected a string, but received: false
    26‚Üí```
    27‚Üí
    28‚ÜíYou can also specify your own message for more clarity. In this case the original message will be preserved in [Error.cause](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Error/cause).
    29‚Üí
    30‚Üí```ts
    31‚Üíassert(data, User, "The user is invalid!");
    32‚Üí// StructError: The user is invalid!
    33‚Üí```
    34‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    53‚Üí## Customizing Errors ‚Ä¶
   102‚Üí## Multiple Failures ‚Ä¶
docs/guides/06-using-typescript.md
     1‚Üí# Using TypeScript
     3‚ÜíSuperstruct is built with TypeScript, and is designed to integrate seamlessly with its guards and assertions. Which means that if you're using TypeScript too you'll get compile-time typings for your data.
     4‚Üí
     5‚Üí> ü§ñ Warning: You must enable TypeScript's [`strictNullChecks`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/tsconfig#strictNullChecks) option in your `tsconfig.json` for Superstruct to work properly with "optional" types. Note that `strictNullChecks` is disabled by default. If you enable `strict`, `strictNullChecks` will automatically be enabled.
     6‚Üí
     7‚Üí## Narrowing Types ‚Ä¶
    37‚Üí## Describing Types ‚Ä¶
    55‚Üí## Inferring Types ‚Ä¶
docs/readme.md
     7‚Üí### Usage
     9‚ÜíSuperstruct allows you to define the shape of data you want to validate:
    10‚Üí
    11‚Üí```js
    12‚Üíimport { assert, object, number, string, array } from 'superstruct'
    13‚Üí
    14‚Üíconst Article = object({
    15‚Üí  id: number(),
    16‚Üí  title: string(),
    17‚Üí  tags: array(string()),
    18‚Üí  author: object({
    19‚Üí    id: number(),
    20‚Üí  }),
    21‚Üí})
    22‚Üí
    23‚Üíconst data = {
    24‚Üí  id: 34,
    25‚Üí  title: 'Hello World',
    26‚Üí  tags: ['news', 'features'],
    27‚Üí  author: {
    28‚Üí    id: 1,
    29‚Üí  },
    30‚Üí}
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üíassert(data, Article)
    33‚Üí// This will throw an error when the data is invalid.
    34‚Üí// If you'd rather not throw, you can use `is()` or `validate()`.
    35‚Üí```
    36‚Üí
    37‚ÜíSuperstruct ships with validators for all the common JavaScript data types, and you can define custom ones too:
    38‚Üí
    39‚Üí```js
    40‚Üíimport { is, define, object, string } from 'superstruct'
    41‚Üíimport isUuid from 'is-uuid'
    42‚Üíimport isEmail from 'is-email'
    43‚Üí
    44‚Üíconst Email = define('Email', isEmail)
    45‚Üíconst Uuid = define('Uuid', isUuid.v4)
    46‚Üí
    47‚Üíconst User = object({
    48‚Üí  id: Uuid,
    49‚Üí  email: Email,
    50‚Üí  name: string(),
    51‚Üí})
    52‚Üí
    53‚Üíconst data = {
    54‚Üí  id: 'c8d63140-a1f7-45e0-bfc6-df72973fea86',
    55‚Üí  email: 'jane@example.com',
    56‚Üí  name: 'Jane',
    57‚Üí}
    58‚Üí
    59‚Üíif (is(data, User)) {
    60‚Üí  // Your data is guaranteed to be valid in this block.
    61‚Üí}
    62‚Üí```
    63‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
